      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Zoning regulations in Portland for adding a small retail component, like a corner grocery, into a residential mixed-use zone can be quite a bit of a maze, but I can give you a general idea. You'll want to check the specific code for your parcel, as the rules can vary even within mixed-use zones. Generally, you'll need to look closely at the setbacks, which dictate how far the building must be from the property lines, and the occupancy limits, which are usually tied to the square footage and the type of use.\n\nFor the setbacks, you'll likely find requirements that differ depending on whether the retail is on the ground floor or if it's a more integrated part of the residential structure. The code will specify minimum distances from the front, side, and rear property lines. It's always wise to consult the official Portland Zoning Code or speak with a planning department representative to ensure you meet all the specific dimensional requirements.\n\nAs for occupancy limits, these are usually governed by the International Building Code (IBC) or local amendments, which will be based on the square footage and the nature of the retail operation. For a small grocery, you'll need to consider factors like aisle width, storage",
      "source": "target",
